+Reasoning: I attempted to run unit tests with the provided check_solution.py but the execution environment did not have Python available; still, static analysis and manual testing produced a concrete failing case. For input x=2, y=0, z=2 the implementation builds an (invalid) string of length 8 (it concatenates AA, AB, AA, AB) and returns 8, while the true maximum valid length is 6, so the algorithm is functionally incorrect. The code also contains many unnecessary and duplicate wildcard imports and some misleading comments, reducing style and maintainability. The core greedy logic is concise but uses an incorrect validity check (inspecting only the last character instead of the last two), which causes both overcounting and missed valid extensions, lowering simplicity and robustness.
